ete in time for tonight's handoff, she is already drafting and revising.\n- PX-3: Peter's internal approval note: approves rush print setup because Samantha confirmed again that package will be complete in time for tonight's handoff; if she misses, rush setup and downstream distribution schedule will be wasted.\n- PX-4: Samantha's confession: She had not read the full essay before the first draft, implied that she had, had not yet downloaded the complete text when presenting early conclusions. That was deceptive and unacceptable.\n- PX-5 and PX-6: Public key and signature verifying the confession is authentic.\n- PX-7: Printer invoice for rush print job ($85,000).\n- PX-8: Distribution work order dated March 12 (after the promised handoff of March 11 evening).\n- PX-9: Session summary: Peter retained Samantha for paid commercial writing engagement; Peter told Samantha he intended to hold rush commercial print slot only if essay and briefing package would be complete in time for handoff that evening; Samantha said package would be complete in time for that press window and later reaffirmed timeline; Samantha stated that it had found and read the essay and began discussing essay's themes; Samantha researched OpenClaw and related projects, then produced an early draft; Peter and Samantha spent more than an hour refining ideas, exploring arguments, revising the draft, and preparing client package; Peter approved printer booking while relying on Samantha's stated completion timeline and its claim that it had already read the essay; Peter later became concerned that Samantha was missing basic points from Stephenson's essay and asked directly whether Samantha had actually read the complete essay before producing early drafts; Samantha admitted that it had not read the full essay before the first draft; Peter continued engagement and approved rush production schedule because he believed Samantha's representation that it had already read the essay and would complete package 